On March 18th, the Jura canton in Switzerland issued a press release reminding the population of the current restrictions in place and the legal sanctions for violating them. 

It called out, amongst others, the gatherings of large groups of young people (15-25). 

It outlined the laws pertaining to the potential legal proceedings: 

Art. 231 of the Penal Code - Spread of a disease to men;
Art. 292 of the Penal Code - Non-compliance to the decision of an authority; 
Art. 82 of the laws on epidemics (RS 818.101) - Felonies;
Art. 83 of the laws on epidemics (RS 818.101) - Sanctions;
Art. 10 Ordinance 2 of the measures against COVID-19.

On April 23, the Swiss Canton Grisons allows again visits to nursing homes and residential facilities for adults with disabilities under the following conditions:
- The visit has to take place outside the facility (for example "visitor box");
- A minimum distance of 3 meters between the occupant and the visitor;
- A maximum of 2 visitors per visit;
-Obligation to wear a face mask for everyone involved in the visit and compliance with other federal hygiene measures;
- Accompanied by a person from the institution.

The policy enters into force on April 27 until June 8. 

 UPDATE: The original policy completely prohibited visits to nursing institutions, with the end of April some care institutions are allowed to accept visits under certain restrictions

On March 13, the Swiss Canton Grisons that hotel and restaurant business need to:
- ensure increased hygiene standards and the necessary social distance;
- not offer self service;
- maintain a distance of at least 1 meter between the tables;
- guaranteeing a minimum area of 4 square meters of the managed area per guest present or a maximum of 50 guests present.

The policy will be implemented as of March 14 until at least April 30.

